## Strategy Details

{%- if account_strategy == "Single Account" %}
### Single Account Strategy

We have selected a **Single Account** strategy for our Snowflake deployment. In this model, all data environments (Dev, Test, Prod) and business domains will exist within one Snowflake account.

**Rationale:**
- Centralized data team manages all data assets and security
- Simplest possible administration with a "single pane of glass" for monitoring
- Developer agility is prioritized, including the ability to use Zero-Copy Cloning
- Cost allocation needs can be handled by tagging resources rather than separate invoices

| Characteristic | Value |
|----------------|-------|
| Primary Data Isolation | Logical (Database/Schema) |
| Cost Tracking | Requires Tagging |
| SDLC Data Sharing | Zero Copy Cloning |
| Complexity | Low |

**Considerations:**
- Lower isolation means changes in non-production environments could theoretically impact production resource limits
- Single security boundary for all data
- Organization Account is recommended for future-proofing

{%- elif account_strategy == "Multi-Account (Environment-based)" %}
### Multi-Account (Environment-based) Strategy

We have selected a **Multi-Account (Environment-based)** strategy for our Snowflake deployment. This strategy separates environments into distinct Snowflake accounts, providing strong isolation between Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC) stages.

**Rationale:**
- Environment isolation is critical for our compliance and security requirements
- Security policies differ by environment (e.g., strict IP allow-listing for Production)
- Audit or regulatory requirements specify distinct boundaries for production environments
- Ability to use different Snowflake Editions per environment to optimize costs

| Characteristic | Value |
|----------------|-------|
| Primary Data Isolation | Physical (Account) |
| Cost Tracking | Separate bills per environment |
| SDLC Data Sharing | Secure Data Sharing |
| Complexity | Medium |

**Considerations:**
- Cannot "clone" databases across accounts; requires data sharing or replication
- Requires managing security and users across multiple accounts
- Organization Account is required

{%- elif account_strategy == "Multi-Account (Domain-based)" %}
### Multi-Account (Domain-based) Strategy

We have selected a **Multi-Account (Domain-based)** strategy for our Snowflake deployment. In this federated model, distinct business units (domains) are given their own accounts, aligning with a Data Mesh architecture.

**Rationale:**
- Decentralized ownership with business units operating as independent entities
- Precise chargeback with clear, separate billing for each business unit
- Different domains may have different release cadences or maintenance windows
- Data sovereignty/residency requirements by geographic region

| Characteristic | Value |
|----------------|-------|
| Primary Data Isolation | Physical (Account) |
| Cost Tracking | Separate bills per domain |
| SDLC Data Sharing | Secure Data Sharing |
| Complexity | Medium |

**Considerations:**
- Requires robust data sharing framework for cross-domain analytics
- Higher complexity in governance and standardization
- Organization Account is required

{%- elif account_strategy == "Multi-Account (Domain + Environment)" %}
### Multi-Account (Domain + Environment) Strategy

We have selected a **Multi-Account (Domain + Environment)** strategy for our Snowflake deployment. This is the most granular strategy where each business unit has separate accounts for their environments.

**Rationale:**
- Complex governance needs requiring maximum isolation
- Highest level of isolation: issues in one domain/environment cannot affect others
- Mature platform team capable of automating management of many accounts
- Most precise tracking of costs by team and lifecycle stage

| Characteristic | Value |
|----------------|-------|
| Primary Data Isolation | Physical (Account) |
| Cost Tracking | Precise Granularity |
| SDLC Data Sharing | Complex Sharing |
| Complexity | High |

**Considerations:**
- Highest operational complexity; requires Infrastructure as Code automation
- Extensive data sharing and replication configuration needed
- Organization Account is required
{%- endif %}